{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98b646e4-5a93-4672-8c22-39b2ce372614","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`**, not `repair`.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, since workload packs may have fallen out of sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls the *same versions* already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer packs to match a new SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still get errors after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) is installed, and reinstall if needed with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f5d34eb-8257-43b3-9432-7e47cd3bc4ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET workload management commands - specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":257,"requestId":"4848:6A01C:76CFE62:8311CB0:69F3FA39"},"id":"53b30f6e-21bc-424f-9bf3-a46abedb4be6","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:56:34.987Z","parentId":"a0d10f05-97a8-434a-b1ef-2d1038a73f5c"}
